</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:BD08FA7B-788B-4285-9548-0F120F97465D" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys Carvalho 1959:2" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Simpsonichthys de Carvalho</taxonomicName>
comprises 50 valid species, occurring in temporary pools formed during the rainy season, in Brazil, Bolivia and Paraguay (Costa, 2005; 2006; Costa &amp; Brasil, in press; the present paper). It has been divided into five subgenera: 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Xenurolebias">Xenurolebias Costa</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Ophthalmolebias">Ophthalmolebias Costa</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Simpsonichthys">Simpsonichthys de Carvalho</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Spectrolebias">Spectrolebias Costa &amp; Nielsen</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Hypsolebias">Hypsolebias Costa</taxonomicName>
(Costa, 2006).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="26">
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Hypsolebias">Hypsolebias</taxonomicName>
is endemic to an area including the Tocantins, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco, Jequitinhonha, and Jaguaribe river basins, and smaller isolated basins of northeastern Brazil (Costa, 2006). Among species of 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Hypsolebias">Hypsolebias</taxonomicName>
, Costa (2006) recognized a clade he termed the 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="antenori">S. antenori species group</taxonomicName>
, which contains five species revised by Costa (2003): 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="antenori">S. antenori (Tulipano)</taxonomicName>
from the rio Jaguaribe basin and adjacent coastal basins of northeastern Brazil; and 
<taxonomicName class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flavicaudatus">S. flavicaudatus (Costa &amp; Brasil)</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8B2D4D4E-8BDF-4D3A-A8AE-74BD05B73BA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys flagellatus Costa 2003:46" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flagellatus">S. flagellatus Costa</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:D1DA8229-BB8D-4D4A-9E00-13375A0BFE09" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys igneus Costa 2000:10" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="igneus">S. igneus Costa</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A6AD55C3-00C6-4E4E-A1D2-683A0D0B4A05" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys ghisolfii Costa, Cyrino &amp; Nielsen 1996:18" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ghisolfii">S. ghisolfii Costa, Cyrino &amp; Nielsen</taxonomicName>
, all from the rio 
<normalizedToken originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco basin. New collections and more intensive morphological studies of material previously identified as 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:8B2D4D4E-8BDF-4D3A-A8AE-74BD05B73BA0" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys flagellatus Costa 2003:46" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="flagellatus">S. flagellatus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:A6AD55C3-00C6-4E4E-A1D2-683A0D0B4A05" class="Actinopterygii" family="Rivulidae" genus="Simpsonichthys" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Simpsonichthys ghisolfii Costa, Cyrino &amp; Nielsen 1996:18" order="Cyprinodontiformes" pageNumber="26" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="ghisolfli">S. ghisolfli</taxonomicName>
revealed three new species, which are herein described. This group of species occurs in hills of the eastern portion of the middle 
<normalizedToken originalValue="São">Sao</normalizedToken>
Francisco basin (Serra do 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Espinhaço">Espinhaco</normalizedToken>
), at altitudes between 550 and 680 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
